Early forms and expressions are often preserved in later literature only in colloquial style,-a fact which ie well illustrated in the Epietlee of Cicero and his correspondents.

Where, however, we find alternative forms in Terence, those which are generally used are, no doubt, the familiar lorms of conversation, while the others, being less colloquial, are employed only for metrical reasons. In Cicero's epraeter, for example, the syncopated forms of tenses in the perfect system of verbs are far more frequent than in more formal Latin.
